[src:web-locks-api/api-lock] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lock] It’s been available across browsers since March 2022.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lock] The **`Lock`** interface of the Web Locks API provides the name and mode of a lock.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lock] This may be a newly requested lock that is received in the callback to `LockManager.request()`, or a record of an active or queued lock returned by `LockManager.query()`.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lock] Returns the access mode passed to `LockManager.request()` when the lock was requested.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lock] The mode is either `"exclusive"` (the default) or `"shared"`.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lock] Returns the name passed to `LockManager.request()` when the lock was requested.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lock] The following examples show how the mode and name properties are passed in the call to `LockManager.request()`.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lock] `LockManager` is the object returned by `navigator.locks`.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lockmanager] The **`LockManager`** interface of the Web Locks API provides methods for requesting a new `Lock` object and querying for an existing `Lock` object.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lockmanager] To get an instance of `LockManager`, call `navigator.locks`.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lockmanager] Requests a `Lock` object with parameters specifying its name and characteristics.
[src:web-locks-api/api-lockmanager] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with an object that contains information about held and pending locks.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] In computer science, a **lock** or **mutex** (from mutual exclusion) is a synchronization primitive that prevents state from being modified or accessed by multiple threads of execution at once.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Locks enforce mutual exclusion concurrency control policies, and with a variety of possible methods there exist multiple unique implementations for different applications.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Generally, locks are *advisory locks*, where each thread cooperates by acquiring the lock before accessing the corresponding data.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Some systems also implement *mandatory locks*, where attempting unauthorized access to a locked resource will force an exception in the entity attempting to make the access.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] The simplest type of lock is a binary semaphore.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] It provides exclusive access to the locked data.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Other schemes also provide shared access for reading data.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Other widely implemented access modes are exclusive, intend-to-exclude and intend-to-upgrade.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Another way to classify locks is by what happens when the lock strategy prevents the progress of a thread.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Most locking designs block the execution of the thread requesting the lock until it is allowed to access the locked resource.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] With a spinlock, the thread simply waits ("spins") until the lock becomes available.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] This is efficient if threads are blocked for a short time, because it avoids the overhead of operating system process rescheduling.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] It is inefficient if the lock is held for a long time, or if the progress of the thread that is holding the lock depends on preemption of the locked thread.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Locks typically require hardware support for efficient implementation.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] This support usually takes the form of one or more atomic instructions such as "test-and-set", "fetch-and-add" or "compare-and-swap".
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] These instructions allow a single process to test if the lock is free, and if free, acquire the lock in a single atomic operation.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Uniprocessor architectures have the option of using uninterruptible sequences of instructions—using special instructions or instruction prefixes to disable interrupts temporarily—but this technique does not work for multiprocessor shared-memory machines.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Proper support for locks in a multiprocessor environment can require quite complex hardware or software support, with substantial synchronization issues.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] The reason an atomic operation is required is because of concurrency, where more than one task executes the same logic.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] The above example does not guarantee that the task has the lock, since more than one task can be testing the lock at the same time.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Since both tasks will detect that the lock is free, both tasks will attempt to set the lock, not knowing that the other task is also setting the lock.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Dekker's or Peterson's algorithm are possible substitutes if atomic locking operations are not available.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Careless use of locks can result in deadlock or livelock.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] A number of strategies can be used to avoid or recover from deadlocks or livelocks, both at design-time and at run-time.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Some languages do support locks syntactically.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] C# introduced System.Threading.Lock in C# 13 on .NET 9.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] The code `lock(this)` can lead to problems if the instance can be accessed publicly.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Similar to Java, C# can also synchronize entire methods, by using the MethodImplOptions.Synchronized attribute.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] There is a tradeoff between decreasing lock overhead and decreasing lock contention when choosing the number of locks in synchronization.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] An important property of a lock is its *granularity*.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] The granularity is a measure of the amount of data the lock is protecting.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] In general, choosing a coarse granularity (a small number of locks, each protecting a large segment of data) results in less *lock overhead* when a single process is accessing the protected data, but worse performance when multiple processes are running concurrently.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] This is because of increased *lock contention*.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] The more coarse the lock, the higher the likelihood that the lock will stop an unrelated process from proceeding.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Conversely, using a fine granularity (a larger number of locks, each protecting a fairly small amount of data) increases the overhead of the locks themselves but reduces lock contention.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Granular locking where each process must hold multiple locks from a common set of locks can create subtle lock dependencies.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] This subtlety can increase the chance that a programmer will unknowingly introduce a *deadlock*.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] In a database management system, for example, a lock could protect, in order of decreasing granularity, part of a field, a field, a record, a data page, or an entire table.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Coarse granularity, such as using table locks, tends to give the best performance for a single user, whereas fine granularity, such as record locks, tends to give the best performance for multiple users.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Database locks can be used as a means of ensuring transaction synchronicity. i.e. when making transaction processing concurrent (interleaving transactions), using 2-phased locks ensures that the concurrent execution of the transaction turns out equivalent to some serial ordering of the transaction.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] However, deadlocks become an unfortunate side-effect of locking in databases.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Deadlocks are either prevented by pre-determining the locking order between transactions or are detected using waits-for graphs.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] An alternate to locking for database synchronicity while avoiding deadlocks involves the use of totally ordered global timestamps.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] There are mechanisms employed to manage the actions of multiple concurrent users on a database—the purpose is to prevent lost updates and dirty reads.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Pessimistic concurrency is best implemented when lock times will be short, as in programmatic processing of records.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Pessimistic concurrency requires a persistent connection to the database and is not a scalable option when users are interacting with data, because records might be locked for relatively large periods of time.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] It is not appropriate for use in Web application development.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Where to use optimistic locking: this is appropriate in environments where there is low contention for data, or where read-only access to data is required.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] where locking data rows for prolonged periods of time would be infeasible.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Also, maintaining record locks requires a persistent connection to the database server, which is not possible in disconnected applications.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Several variations and refinements of these major lock types exist, with respective variations of blocking behavior.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] If a first lock blocks another lock, the two locks are called *incompatible*; otherwise the locks are *compatible*.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Often, lock types blocking interactions are presented in the technical literature by a *Lock compatibility table*.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Some concurrency control strategies avoid some or all of these problems.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] For example, a funnel or serializing tokens can avoid the biggest problem: deadlocks.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Alternatives to locking include non-blocking synchronization methods, like lock-free programming techniques and transactional memory.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] However, such alternative methods often require that the actual lock mechanisms be implemented at a more fundamental level of the operating software.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Therefore, they may only relieve the *application* level from the details of implementing locks, with the problems listed above still needing to be dealt with beneath the application.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Therefore, an application can often be more robust when it recognizes the burdens it places upon an operating system and is capable of graciously recognizing the reporting of impossible demands.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] One of lock-based programming's biggest problems is that "locks don't compose": it is hard to combine small, correct lock-based modules into equally correct larger programs without modifying the modules or at least knowing about their internals.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Simon Peyton Jones (an advocate of software transactional memory) gives the following example of a banking application: design a class Account that allows multiple concurrent clients to deposit or withdraw money to an account, and give an algorithm to transfer money from one account to another.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] The second part of the problem is much more complicated.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] In a concurrent program, this algorithm is incorrect because when one thread is halfway through transfer, another might observe a state where amount has been withdrawn from the first account, but not yet deposited into the other account: money has gone missing from the system.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] This solution gets more complicated when more locks are involved, and the transfer function needs to know about all of the locks, so they cannot be hidden.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] A mutex is a locking mechanism that sometimes uses the same basic implementation as the binary semaphore.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] However, they differ in how they are used.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] While a binary semaphore may be colloquially referred to as a mutex, a true mutex has a more specific use-case and definition, in that only the task that locked the mutex is supposed to unlock it.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Premature task termination: Mutexes may also provide deletion safety, where the task holding the mutex cannot be accidentally deleted.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Termination deadlock: If a mutex-holding task terminates for any reason, the OS can release the mutex and signal waiting tasks of this condition.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Recursion deadlock: a task is allowed to lock a reentrant mutex multiple times as it unlocks it an equal number of times.
[src:web-locks-api/lock-computer-science] Accidental release: An error is raised on the release of the mutex if the releasing task is not its owner.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] The **`request()`** method of the `LockManager` interface requests a `Lock` object with parameters specifying its name and characteristics.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] The requested `Lock` is passed to a callback, while the function itself returns a `Promise` that resolves (or rejects) with the result of the callback after the lock is released, or rejects if the request is aborted.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] The `mode` property of the `options` parameter may be either `"exclusive"` or `"shared"`.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] Request an `"exclusive"` lock when it should only be held by one code instance at a time.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] This applies to code in both tabs and workers.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] Use this to represent mutually exclusive access to a resource.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] When an `"exclusive"` lock for a given name is held, no other lock with the same name can be held.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] Request a `"shared"` lock when multiple instances of the code can share access to a resource.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] When a `"shared"` lock for a given name is held, other `"shared"` locks for the same name can be granted, but no `"exclusive"` locks with that name can be held or granted.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] This shared/exclusive lock pattern is common in database transaction architecture, for example to allow multiple simultaneous readers (each requests a `"shared"` lock) but only one writer (a single `"exclusive"` lock).
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] This is known as the readers-writer pattern.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] In the IndexedDB API, this is exposed as `"readonly"` and `"readwrite"` transactions which have the same semantics.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] An identifier for the lock you want to request.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] An object describing characteristics of the lock you want to create.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] If `true`, the lock request will only be granted if it is not already held.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] If it cannot be granted, the callback will be invoked with `null` instead of a `Lock` instance.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] If `true`, then any held locks with the same name will be released, and the request will be granted, preempting any queued requests for it.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] An `AbortSignal` (the `signal` property of an `AbortController`); if specified and the `AbortController` is aborted, the lock request is dropped if it was not already granted.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] The lock is automatically released when the callback returns (or an exception is thrown).
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] Usually the callback is an async function, which causes the lock to be released only when the async function has completely finished.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] A `Promise` that resolves (or rejects) with the result of the callback after the lock is released, or rejects if the request is aborted.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] Thrown if the environments document is not fully active.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] Thrown if a lock manager cannot be obtained for the current environment.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] Thrown if `name` starts with a hyphen (`-`), both options `steal` and `ifAvailable` are `true`, or if option `signal` exists and *either* option `steal` or `ifAvailable` is `true`.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] Thrown if the option `signal` exists and is aborted.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] The following example shows the basic use of the `request()` method with an asynchronous function as the callback.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] Once the callback is invoked, no other running code on this origin can hold `my_resource` until the callback returns.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] The following example shows how to use the `mode` option for readers and writers.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] Notice that both functions use a lock called `my_resource`.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] The `doRead()` requests a lock in `'shared'` mode meaning that multiple calls may occur simultaneously across different event handlers, tabs, or workers.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] The `doWrite()` function use the same lock but in `'exclusive'` mode which will delay invocation of the `request()` call in `doRead()` until the write operation has completed.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] This applies across event handlers, tabs, or workers.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] To grab a lock only if it isn't already being held, use the `ifAvailable` option.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] In this function `await` means the method will not return until the callback is complete.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] Since the lock is only granted if it was available, this call avoids needing to wait on the lock being released elsewhere.
[src:web-locks-api/lockmanager-request] To only wait for a lock for a short period of time, use the `signal` option.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] In computer science, **mutual exclusion** is a property of concurrency control, which is instituted for the purpose of preventing race conditions.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] It is the requirement that one thread of execution never enters a critical section while a concurrent thread of execution is already accessing said critical section, which refers to an interval of time during which a thread of execution accesses a shared resource or shared memory.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] The shared resource is a data object, which two or more concurrent threads are trying to modify (where two concurrent read operations are permitted but, no two concurrent write operations or one read and one write are permitted, since it leads to data inconsistency).
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] The requirement of mutual exclusion was first identified and solved by Edsger W.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Dijkstra in his seminal 1965 paper "Solution of a problem in concurrent programming control", which is credited as the first topic in the study of concurrent algorithms.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] A simple example of why mutual exclusion is important in practice can be visualized using a singly linked list of four items, where the second and third are to be removed.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Although both removal operations complete successfully, the desired state of the linked list is not achieved: node *i* + 1 remains in the list, because the *next* pointer of node *i* – 1 points to node *i* + 1.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] This problem (called a *race condition*) can be avoided by using the requirement of mutual exclusion to ensure that simultaneous updates to the same part of the list cannot occur.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] The term mutual exclusion is also used in reference to the simultaneous writing of a memory address by one thread while the aforementioned memory address is being manipulated or read by one or more other threads.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] The problem which mutual exclusion addresses is a problem of resource sharing: how can a software system control multiple processes' access to a shared resource, when each process needs exclusive control of that resource while doing its work?
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] The mutual-exclusion solution to this makes the shared resource available only while the process is in a specific code segment called the critical section.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] It controls access to the shared resource by controlling each mutual execution of that part of its program where the resource would be used.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Every process's program can be partitioned into four sections, resulting in four states.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Operation is outside the critical section; the process is not using or requesting the shared resource.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] The process attempts to enter the critical section.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] The process is allowed to access the shared resource in this section.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] The process leaves the critical section and makes the shared resource available to other processes.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] If a process wishes to enter the critical section, it must first execute the trying section and wait until it acquires access to the critical section.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] After the process has executed its critical section and is finished with the shared resources, it needs to execute the exit section to release them for other processes' use.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] The process then returns to its non-critical section.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] On uni-processor systems, the simplest solution to achieve mutual exclusion is to disable interrupts during a process's critical section.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] This will prevent any interrupt service routines from running (effectively preventing a process from being preempted).
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Although this solution is effective, it leads to many problems.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] If a critical section is long, then the system clock will drift every time a critical section is executed because the timer interrupt is no longer serviced, so tracking time is impossible during the critical section.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Also, if a process halts during its critical section, control will never be returned to another process, effectively halting the entire system.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] A more elegant method for achieving mutual exclusion is the busy-wait.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Busy-waiting is effective for both uniprocessor and multiprocessor systems.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] The use of shared memory and an atomic test-and-set instruction provide the mutual exclusion.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] A process can test-and-set on a location in shared memory, and since the operation is atomic, only one process can set the flag at a time.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Any process that is unsuccessful in setting the flag can either go on to do other tasks and try again later, release the processor to another process and try again later, or continue to loop while checking the flag until it is successful in acquiring it.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Preemption is still possible, so this method allows the system to continue to function—even if a process halts while holding the lock.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Several other atomic operations can be used to provide mutual exclusion of data structures; most notable of these is compare-and-swap (CAS).
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] CAS can be used to achieve wait-free mutual exclusion for any shared data structure by creating a linked list where each node represents the desired operation to be performed.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] CAS is then used to change the pointers in the linked list during the insertion of a new node.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Only one process can be successful in its CAS; all other processes attempting to add a node at the same time will have to try again.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Each process can then keep a local copy of the data structure, and upon traversing the linked list, can perform each operation from the list on its local copy.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] In addition to hardware-supported solutions, some software solutions exist that use busy waiting to achieve mutual exclusion.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] These algorithms do not work if out-of-order execution is used on the platform that executes them.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Programmers have to specify strict ordering on the memory operations within a thread.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] It is often preferable to use synchronization facilities provided by an operating system’s multithreading library, which can take advantage of hardware support when available but fall back on software mechanisms when necessary.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] As a result, most modern mutual exclusion techniques aim to reduce latency and busy-waiting by relying on queuing and context switching.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] However, if the overhead of suspending and later restoring a thread is demonstrably greater than the time the thread would spend waiting for the lock to become available in a specific scenario, then spinlocks can be an acceptable solution in that context.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] One binary test&set register is sufficient to provide the deadlock-free solution to the mutual exclusion problem.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] But a solution built with a test&set register can possibly lead to the starvation of some processes which become caught in the trying section.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] In fact, $\Omega ({\sqrt {n}})$ distinct memory states are required to avoid lockout.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] To avoid unbounded waiting, *n* distinct memory states are required.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Most algorithms for mutual exclusion are designed with the assumption that no failure occurs while a process is running inside the critical section.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] However, in reality such failures may be commonplace.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] For example, a sudden loss of power or faulty interconnect might cause a process in a critical section to experience an unrecoverable error or otherwise be unable to continue.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] If such a failure occurs, conventional, non-failure-tolerant mutual exclusion algorithms may deadlock or otherwise fail key liveness properties.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] To deal with this problem, several solutions using crash-recovery mechanisms have been proposed.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Many forms of mutual exclusion have side-effects.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] For example, classic semaphores permit deadlocks, in which one process gets a semaphore, another process gets a second semaphore, and then both wait till the other semaphore to be released.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Other common side-effects include starvation, in which a process never gets sufficient resources to run to completion; priority inversion, in which a higher-priority thread waits for a lower-priority thread; and high latency, in which response to interrupts is not prompt.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Much research is aimed at eliminating the above effects, often with the goal of guaranteeing non-blocking progress.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Blocking system calls used to sleep an entire process.
[src:web-locks-api/mutual-exclusion] Until such calls became threadsafe, there was no proper mechanism for sleeping a single thread within a process (see polling).
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] The **Web Locks API** allows scripts running in one tab or worker to asynchronously acquire a lock, hold it while work is performed, then release it.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] While held, no other script executing in the same origin can acquire the same lock, which allows a web app running in multiple tabs or workers to coordinate work and the use of resources.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] A lock is an abstract concept representing some potentially shared resource, identified by a name chosen by the web app.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] Work is done while holding the lock in an asynchronous task.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] The lock is automatically released when the task completes.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] While a lock is held, requests for the same lock from this execution context, or from other tabs/workers, will be queued.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] The first queued request will be granted only when the lock is released.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] Locks are scoped to origins; the locks acquired by a tab from `https://example.com` have no effect on the locks acquired by a tab from `https://example.org:8080` as they are separate origins.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] The main entry point is `navigator.locks.request()` which requests a lock.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] It takes a lock name, an optional set of options, and a callback.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] The callback is invoked when the lock is granted.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] The lock is automatically released when the callback returns, so usually the callback is an *async function*, which causes the lock to be released only when the async function has completely finished.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] The `request()` method itself returns a promise which resolves once the lock has been released; within an async function, a script can `await` the call to make the asynchronous code flow linearly.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] The `navigator.locks.query()` method can be used by scripts to introspect the state of the lock manager for the origin.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] This can be useful when debugging, for example, identifying why a lock could not be acquired.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] The results are a snapshot of the lock manager state, which identifies held and requested locks and some additional data (e.g., mode) about each, at the time the snapshot was taken.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] A deadlock occurs when a process can no longer make progress because each part is waiting on a request that cannot be satisfied.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] This can occur with this API in complex use-cases, for example, if multiple locks are requested out-of-order.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] If tab 1 holds lock A and tab 2 holds lock B, then tab 1 attempts to also acquire lock B and tab 2 attempts to also acquire lock A, neither request can be granted.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] Web applications can avoid this through several strategies, such as ensuring lock requests are not nested, or are always well ordered, or have timeouts.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] Note that such deadlocks only affect the locks themselves and code depending on them; the browser, other tabs, and other script in the page is not affected.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] Provides the name and mode of a previously requested lock, which is received in the callback to `LockManager.request()`.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] Provides methods for requesting a new `Lock` object and querying for an existing `Lock` object.
[src:web-locks-api/web-locks-api] Returns a `LockManager` object that provides methods for requesting a new `Lock` object and querying for an existing `Lock` object.
